How did Leicester City FC Win the 2015-2016 English Premier League, and How did Arsenal FC Stack up Against Them?¶

Jarod French
CMSC 320 Spring 2022
Published May 16, 2022
Last updated May 16, 2022

The objective of this data analysis is to shed light on the methods used to analyze the data, as well as get to the bottom of the reasons why Leicester City won the Premier League in 2015-2016. This tutorial will walk us through the Data Science Pipeline,

  1. Data collection/curation + parsing (if necessary)
  2. Data management/representation
  3. Exploratory data analysis
  4. Hypothesis testing
  5. Communication of insights attained

while analyzing Leicester City's season.

Introduction¶

    The English Premier League is the top tier soccer league in England, and many believe it to be the best soccer league in the world. It is home to some of the best soccer players in the world, with names like Cristiano Ronaldo, Kevin de Bruyne, and Virgil van Dijk. The league consists of 20 teams each season, each of them playing every other team twice for a total of 38 games. The winning team is awarded 3 points, while the losing team gets no points. In the event of a tie, both teams are awarded 1 point. At the end of the season, the team with the most points is awarded the Premier League trophy for winning the league. However, the three teams that collect the least amount of points are relegated to the 2nd division of English soccer, and three teams from the second division are promoted to replace the relegated teams.
    The league is host to a number of massive clubs such as Arsenal FC, Chelsea FC, Manchester City FC, Manchester United FC, and Liverpool FC. Those 5 clubs have won the Premier League an astonishing 27 times out of 29 years. The only other two teams to win the Premier League? Blackburn Rovers in 1995 and Leicester City FC in 2016.
    Leicester City was not one of the founding 22 clubs of the Premier League in 1992, and before 2014 they had not been in the Premier League since 2004. Actually in 2008, they were in the third division of English soccer, which makes it all the more remarkable how fast they got back to the first division of English soccer in just 6 years. Now this analysis of the 2015-16 season will explain how the team that was in the third division 8 years prior, ended up winning the Premier League. It will also teach you how to do your own analysis of a team's season using python and data.

Obviously Leicester City won the Premier League by having the most points as the league table indicates, but there are other stats that tell us why they had the most points. We are going to want to plot a several statistics, so lets go ahead and write a function that will display a plot for us to simplify each step.

In [52]:
def simple_plot(xdata, ydata, xmax, ymax, xmin, ymin, xticks, yticks, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,8)) # make the plot larger 
    # These lines center the plot on the data.
    plt.xlim(xmin=xmin,xmax=xmax + xticks) 
    plt.xticks(range(xmin, xmax + xticks, xticks))
    plt.ylim(ymin=ymin, ymax=ymax + yticks)
    plt.yticks(range(ymin, ymax + yticks, yticks))
    # plot the data
    plt.scatter(xdata, ydata)
    # labels for the axes
    plt.title(title, fontsize=20)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()

To start let's take a look at their offensive record, the Goals For (GF) column. We will plot the Rank column as the x data and the goals for will be the y data.

As we can see, Leicester City was one of the top goalscoring teams, but the most important part of this plot is the trend that shows that the teams that score more goals tend to rank higher at the end of the season. Now lets look at their defense. We will plot Rank vs Goals Against.

As we can see, Leicester City has one of the best defensize records in the Premier League in 2015-2016, and as the plot suggests, better teams conced less goals. As you can see, some of the data is not in the format we would like, such as the names of the players and their nationalities. Now we can see the data in a nice format, but some is different than what we want so we have to clean the data.
We don't need the matches column, since we have season stats. we need to extract the players names and nationalities from the way that pandas read the data, and we need to separate the positions for those players that have more than 1 position. (add 2nd column for 2nd position). Also rename the columns that are duplicate names, for what they actually represent.

In [62]:
# clean player table: NaNs where the column doesn't apply, 0s where the player recorded 0 or if that column doesn't apply.

player_stats = player_stats.drop('Matches', axis=1)
player_stats['Player'] = player_stats['Player'].str.extract(r'(.*?)\\.*')
player_stats['Nation'] = player_stats['Nation'].str.extract(r'([A-Z]+)')
list = player_stats['Pos'].str.extract(r'([A-Z]{2})([A-Z]{2})?')
player_stats['Pos'] = list[0]
player_stats['2nd_Pos'] = list[1]
# player_stats['Pos'] = player_stats['Pos'].str.extract(r'([A-Z]{2})')
player_stats = player_stats[['Rk', 'Player', 'Nation', 'Pos','2nd_Pos', 'Squad', 'Age', 'Born', 'MP', 'Starts','Min', '90s',
                            'Gls', 'Ast', 'G-PK', 'PK', 'PKatt', 'CrdY', 'CrdR', 'Gls.1', 'Ast.1', 'G+A', 'G-PK.1', 'G+A-PK']]
player_stats['Gls_per_90'] = player_stats['Gls.1']
player_stats['Ast_per_90'] = player_stats['Ast.1']
player_stats['G+A_per_90'] = player_stats['G+A']
player_stats['G-PK_per_90'] = player_stats['G-PK.1']
player_stats['G+A-PK_per_90'] = player_stats['G+A-PK']
player_stats = player_stats.drop(['Rk', 'Gls.1', 'Ast.1', 'G+A', 'G-PK.1', 'G+A-PK'], axis=1)
player_stats.head()
